        "description":  "Whether you\u0027re supporting a natural breeding cycle or providing seasonal enrichment, the right nesting materials can make or break your bird\u0027s reproductive success. This guide covers the best nesting boxes, materials, and breeding supplies for every bird species — plus what to NEVER put in a nest.",
        "content":  "\u003ch2\u003eWhy Proper Nesting Materials Matter — Even If You\u0027re Not Breeding\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eNesting behavior in companion birds is instinctive, not optional. Every spring — triggered by increasing daylight hours, warmer temperatures, and (in indoor birds) artificial lighting schedules — parrots, finches, canaries, cockatiels, and budgies experience a hormonal surge that drives them to seek nesting sites and build nests. Even a single, hand-raised male cockatiel who has never seen a female of his species will shred paper, collect fibers, and try to build a nest in the corner of his cage. This isn\u0027t \"wanting babies\" — it\u0027s millions of years of reproductive programming expressing itself.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFor breeders, proper nesting materials directly determine clutch success: the right substrate controls humidity around the eggs (too dry = desiccated embryos; too wet = bacterial growth), the right nest box design prevents egg-crushing by the parents, and the right lining prevents splayed legs in hatchlings. For non-breeding companion bird owners, providing controlled, appropriate nesting materials during breeding season gives the bird a healthy outlet for nesting instincts — shredding a coconut fiber mat or arranging paper strips in a breeding box — rather than the bird redirecting that urge into feather plucking, cage-bar chewing, or egg-laying in an unsuitable location (like the bottom of the food bowl, resulting in cracked eggs and egg-binding).\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThis guide covers the best nesting boxes, safe nesting materials, and essential breeding supplies for every companion bird species — plus the materials you must NEVER put in a nest, and how to manage breeding behavior in birds you don\u0027t intend to breed.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003eThe Hormonal Trigger: Understanding When Nesting Happens\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePhotoperiod (daylight length):\u003c/strong\u003e 12+ hours of light triggers breeding hormones in most parrot species. In the wild, breeding season aligns with spring/summer. In captivity, artificial lighting that stays on for 12+ hours year-round can trigger chronic hormonal behavior — including chronic egg-laying, aggression, and feather destruction\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eFood abundance:\u003c/strong\u003e Rich, high-fat, high-protein foods (seeds, nuts, egg food, sprouted seeds) signal \"there\u0027s enough food to raise chicks.\" A diet heavy in these foods during non-breeding season can trigger unwanted hormonal behavior\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePhysical triggers:\u003c/strong\u003e The presence of a nest box, a dark enclosed space, or even a pile of shredded material in a cage corner can trigger egg-laying. Some hens will lay eggs into a food bowl if no nest box is available — the instinct is that strong\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eManaging hormones in non-breeding birds:\u003c/strong\u003e Limit daylight to 10-12 hours (cover the cage at 7 PM, uncover at 7 AM), reduce high-fat/high-protein foods, remove any enclosed spaces or shredding materials during non-breeding season, and avoid petting the bird on the back or under the wings (which stimulates breeding behavior)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003ch2\u003eTop 7 Bird Nesting Materials \u0026 Breeding Supplies\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003e1. Prevue Pet Products Wooden Breeding Box — Best All-Purpose Nest Box\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003ePrevue\u0027s wooden breeding boxes are the standard nest box for small to medium parrots (budgies, cockatiels, lovebirds, parrotlets, conures). Constructed from unfinished pine wood (safe for birds to chew — and they WILL chew the entrance hole), with a hinged top lid for inspection access and a concave interior floor (the slight depression prevents eggs from rolling around and keeps the clutch together under the brooding hen). The entrance hole is sized appropriately for the species — a small hole for budgies/lovebirds, a medium hole for cockatiels/conures. The wood naturally regulates humidity (absorbing excess moisture and releasing it slowly — maintaining the ~50-60% RH that parrot eggs need for successful incubation).\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePros:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eNatural pine wood — humidity-regulating, safe to chew, maintains proper nest microclimate\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eConcave interior floor — keeps eggs together under the brooding hen, prevents rolling\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eHinged top lid — enables inspection of eggs and chicks without disturbing the nest too much\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAppropriate entrance hole — sized for budgies, cockatiels, lovebirds, or conures (check listing for species-specific sizing)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eWood is untreated, unpainted — completely bird-safe\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eEasy to mount — included hardware attaches to cage exterior or interior (depending on cage design)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e$12-25 depending on size\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCons:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eWood is chewable — aggressive chewers (conures, larger parrots) can enlarge the entrance hole or chew through the box walls over multiple breeding cycles. Replace every 2-3 breeding seasons\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eNot dishwasher-safe — cleaning requires scraping, sanding, and sun-drying (no chemicals on the wood)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ePure wood absorbs droppings — cannot be fully sterilized after a chick-rearing cycle (consider disposable cardboard nest boxes for one-time use if biosecurity is a concern)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eNest box becomes \"theirs\" — once a pair claims it, removing the box mid-season causes distress. Plan breeding season timing carefully\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRating: 5/5\u003c/strong\u003e | \u003cstrong\u003eBest For:\u003c/strong\u003e Budgies, cockatiels, lovebirds, parrotlets, conures — standard wooden nest box for small-medium parrots\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003e2. Kordon Nature\u0027s Nest Coconut Fiber — Best Natural Nesting Material\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eKordon Nature\u0027s Nest is a compressed brick of coconut fiber (coir) nesting material — when soaked in water, it expands to fill a standard nest box with soft, moisture-regulating, antimicrobial coconut fiber that\u0027s identical to what wild birds nest in (many tropical birds line nests with palm fiber, coconut coir, and other fibrous plant materials). The fiber regulates humidity around the eggs perfectly: it absorbs excess moisture (preventing fungal growth), releases moisture slowly when the nest box gets too dry (preventing egg desiccation), and provides a soft, grippy surface that prevents hatchlings from developing splayed legs (a condition where the legs splay outward instead of sitting under the body, caused by chicks attempting to stand on a slick surface like bare wood or newspaper).\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePros:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e100% natural coconut fiber — antimicrobial, moisture-regulating, completely safe for ingestion\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eHumidity regulation — absorbs and slowly releases moisture, maintaining ideal nest microclimate\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ePrevents splayed legs — soft, grippy surface gives chicks traction for proper leg development\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCompressed brick expands 4-5X when hydrated — a small brick fills a large nest box\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eNo dust — unlike hay, straw, or wood shavings that produce respiratory-irritating dust\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e$8-12 per brick (fills 1-2 nest boxes depending on box size)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCons:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eRequires pre-soaking and drying — the brick must be hydrated, then dried to the correct moisture level (damp, not wet, not bone-dry) before use\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCoconut fiber can harbor mites if stored improperly — always bake or freeze new fiber before use as a biosecurity measure\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCoconut fiber breaks down over time — replace the nest lining between every clutch\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eMessy — coconut fiber particles scatter around the cage as the hen arranges the nest to her satisfaction\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRating: 5/5\u003c/strong\u003e | \u003cstrong\u003eBest For:\u003c/strong\u003e All breeding birds — the safest, most natural nest lining material on the market\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003e3. Living World Bamboo Nesting Fiber — Best Enrichment Nesting Supply\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eLiving World\u0027s bamboo nesting fiber is a loose, fluffy bundle of natural bamboo fibers that birds shred, arrange, and weave into their nest — providing the behavioral enrichment of nest-building (the bird shapes the material to its preference) rather than the simply-lined nest box approach. For finches, canaries, lovebirds, and budgies — species that actively build rather than simply occupy a nesting cavity — the act of shredding and arranging nesting fiber is an essential part of the breeding behavioral sequence. Providing loose fiber triggers proper nest-building behavior, which in turn triggers proper brooding behavior. For non-breeding birds, a small bundle of nesting fiber during breeding season provides a shredding enrichment activity — better they shred bamboo fiber than pluck their own chest feathers.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePros:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eNatural bamboo fiber — soft, shredable, safe for ingestion in small amounts\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eEnrichment value — shredding and arranging fiber is behavioral enrichment, not just a nest supply\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eTriggers natural nest-building sequence — loose fiber prompts the weaving instinct that pre-fabricated nest liners don\u0027t\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eDust-free — unlike hay, straw, or cotton fiber, bamboo doesn\u0027t produce respiratory irritant dust\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eLong strand length — individual fibers are 2-6 inches long, perfect for weaving into a nest cup\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e$6-10 per bundle\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCons:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eFiber strands can tangle around chick legs and toes if packed too densely — provide a modest amount (a loose handful, not a compressed brick) and let the hen arrange it\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eBirds scatter fiber everywhere — the cage floor, the water bowl, the food dish, and the surrounding floor will be covered with bamboo fuzz during nest-building week\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eNot a complete nest lining — pair bamboo fiber with coconut coir as a base layer, with the fiber on top for the hen to arrange\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eSome hens over-build — removing excess fiber from the nest box periodically prevents the clutch from being buried under 3 inches of nesting material\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRating: 4.5/5\u003c/strong\u003e | \u003cstrong\u003eBest For:\u003c/strong\u003e Finches, canaries, lovebirds, budgies — species that actively weave and arrange nesting fiber\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003e4. Penn-Plax Bird Breeding Grass Mat — Best Pre-Formed Nest Liner\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003ePenn-Plax grass mats are pre-formed, rigid liners made from woven seagrass — a natural, edible grass fiber formed into a circular nest-cup shape that fits directly into standard nest boxes and breeding cages. Unlike loose coconut fiber or bamboo fiber (which the hen rearranges, potentially over weeks), the grass mat stays in place — providing a consistent, hygienic nest surface that can be lifted out and replaced between clutches in 10 seconds. The woven grass surface prevents eggs from rolling (the slightly textured weave grips eggs) and provides chick-leg traction (preventing splayed legs). For breeders who prioritize cleanliness and efficiency over the \"natural nest-building\" enrichment experience, pre-formed grass liners simplify nest management dramatically.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePros:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ePre-formed — drop into the nest box, no shredding/arranging required, no mess\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eReplaceable in seconds — lift the used mat out, drop a clean mat in, done\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eWoven texture — prevents egg-rolling and provides chick-leg traction against splayed legs\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eNatural seagrass — edible, digestible, no synthetic fibers or glues\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eConsistent — every mat is identical, eliminates the \"did the hen build the nest correctly?\" variable\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e$5-8 per 2-pack\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCons:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eNo behavioral enrichment — the hen has no opportunity to shred, arrange, or build (some breeders prefer this, others consider it a lost behavioral opportunity)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eFits only standard-sized nest boxes — won\u0027t fit custom or oversized boxes\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eGrass mats can harbor bacteria if not changed frequently — replace every 1-2 weeks during active breeding, immediately after chicks fledge\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eSome hens reject pre-formed liners and insist on building their own nest from loose fiber — have loose coconut fiber as backup\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRating: 4/5\u003c/strong\u003e | \u003cstrong\u003eBest For:\u003c/strong\u003e Efficiency-focused breeders, multi-pair breeding operations, quick nest maintenance\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003e5. A\u0026E Cage Company Stainless Steel Breeding Cage — Best Dedicated Breeding Enclosure\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eA\u0026E Cage Company\u0027s stainless steel breeding cages are purpose-built for breeding pairs — they include a divider panel (to separate the male and female during initial introduction, preventing aggression before bonding), a built-in nest box mounting panel on the exterior of the cage (the nest box attaches outside the cage wall, minimizing interior space loss and making egg/chick inspection possible without opening the cage), and a slide-out grate and tray for hygienic waste management. The stainless steel construction is rust-proof, chew-proof (unlike powder-coated wire cages that parrots strip to bare metal), and infinitely sterilizable — essential for preventing disease transmission between breeding pairs in multi-pair operations.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePros:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eStainless steel — rust-proof, chew-proof, fully sterilizable (autoclave, bleach solution, F10SC)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eDivider panel — gradual introduction prevents aggression and forced mating\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eExterior nest box mount — nest box inspection without opening the cage or disturbing the hen\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eSlide-out grate and tray — easy waste management without disturbing the nesting pair\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAppropriate bar spacing for breeding species — 1/2\" for small parrots, 5/8\" for medium parrots\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e$100-200 depending on size\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCons:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eExpensive — stainless steel is premium pricing versus powder-coated cages\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eHeavy — stainless steel cages weigh significantly more than standard wire cages\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eNot a \"starter\" cage — dedicated breeding cages assume you\u0027re committed to breeding, not just accommodating a seasonal nesting urge\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eRequires assembly — the cage ships flat-packed and requires 30-45 minutes of assembly with included tools\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRating: 4.5/5\u003c/strong\u003e | \u003cstrong\u003eBest For:\u003c/strong\u003e Serious breeders, multi-pair operations, hygienic breeding environments\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003e6. Kaytee Exact Hand-Feeding Formula — Best Chick Rearing Food\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eKaytee Exact Hand-Feeding Formula is the standard chick-rearing food for every parrot species from budgies to macaws — a complete, balanced formula that replaces the crop milk and regurgitated food that parent birds provide in the wild. The formula is a fine powder that mixes with warm water to create a smooth, syringe-feedable liquid at the exact temperature and consistency that chicks accept (105-107°F at feeding, consistency of thin pudding). It contains balanced protein, fat, carbohydrates, vitamins, and probiotics — everything a growing chick needs from day 1 hatch through weaning. For breeders who pull chicks for hand-feeding (tamer pet-quality babies, or when parent birds abandon/reject chicks), Kaytee Exact is the essential supply.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePros:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eComplete nutrition — balanced protein/fat/carbs/vitamins/probiotics for chicks from day 1 to weaning\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eFine powder mixes smoothly — no lumps that clog the feeding syringe\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eProbiotics included — supports chick gut development and immune health during the critical first weeks\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAvailable in size-specific formulas — Exact for Macaw, Exact for Cockatiel, Exact for small birds (different particle sizes and nutrient profiles for different species)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eEstablished brand with decades of use — Kaytee Exact has raised millions of chicks\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e$10-15 per bag\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCons:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eHand-feeding requires training — underfeeding, overfeeding, feeding too hot (crop burn), feeding too cold (slow crop, bacterial growth), and aspiration (formula in the trachea → pneumonia) are all lethal mistakes that untrained hand-feeders make. Learn from an experienced breeder or avian vet before hand-feeding your first chick\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eMixed formula spoils within 2 hours at room temperature — each feeding requires freshly prepared formula (no batch-prepping and storing)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eFormula must be precisely 105-107°F — too hot burns the crop (deadly), too cold slows crop emptying (bacterial overgrowth → sour crop → dead chick)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eNot suitable for parent-raised chicks — only use for breeder-directed hand-feeding programs\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRating: 5/5\u003c/strong\u003e | \u003cstrong\u003eBest For:\u003c/strong\u003e Hand-feeding breeders — the established formula for every parrot species (REQUIRES TRAINING)\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003e7. Zoo Med Avian Calcium Supplement — Best Breeding Nutrition Booster\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eZoo Med\u0027s Avian Calcium supplement provides the calcium boost that breeding hens desperately need — a single clutch of eggs demands more calcium than the hen\u0027s entire skeleton contains. Without dietary calcium supplementation during breeding, the hen leaches calcium from her own bones to form eggshells — resulting in thin-shelled eggs (that crack during incubation), egg-binding (a life-threatening emergency where a soft-shelled egg gets stuck in the oviduct), and long-term metabolic bone disease in the hen. This calcium powder is formulated with vitamin D3 (required for calcium absorption — without D3, dietary calcium passes through the bird undigested), and it\u0027s tasteless and odorless when mixed into soft food (egg food, chop, or sprouted seeds).\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePros:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCalcium + D3 — the D3 enables the bird to actually absorb and use the calcium\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ePrevents calcium crash — protects the hen from leaching her bone calcium for eggshell formation\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ePrevents thin-shelled eggs — adequate calcium = strong eggshells that survive incubation\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ePrevents egg-binding — soft-shelled eggs are the primary cause of egg-binding (the shell collapses and can\u0027t be passed)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eTasteless and odorless — mix into soft food without the hen rejecting the meal\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eEssential for ALL breeding birds — even if you provide cuttlebone and mineral blocks, powdered calcium ensures precise dosage\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e$6-10 per bottle (3-6 month supply for 1-2 breeding pairs)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCons:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ePowder must be mixed with moist food — it doesn\u0027t stick to dry seed or pellets\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eOverdosing is possible (calcium toxicity causes kidney damage) — follow dosing guidelines precisely, don\u0027t \"add extra for good measure\"\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eNot sufficient as a bird\u0027s sole calcium source — still provide cuttlebone and mineral blocks for free-choice calcium intake\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eSupplement quality varies between brands — Zoo Med is reliable, but generic calcium powders may have inconsistent D3 levels\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRating: 5/5\u003c/strong\u003e | \u003cstrong\u003eBest For:\u003c/strong\u003e All breeding hens — mandatory nutritional support during egg-laying cycles\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch2\u003eComparison Table\u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\u003cth\u003eProduct\u003c/th\u003e\u003cth\u003eType\u003c/th\u003e\u003cth\u003eBest For\u003c/th\u003e\u003cth\u003eKey Benefit\u003c/th\u003e\u003cth\u003ePrice\u003c/th\u003e\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\u003ctd\u003ePrevue Wooden Breeding Box\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eNest box (pine wood)\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eBudgies, cockatiels, lovebirds\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eHumidity-regulating wood\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003e$12-25\u003c/td\u003e\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\u003ctd\u003eKordon Coconut Fiber\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eNest lining (coir brick)\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eAll breeding birds\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eAntimicrobial, prevents splayed legs\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003e$8-12\u003c/td\u003e\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\u003ctd\u003eLiving World Bamboo Fiber\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eLoose nesting material\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eFinches, canaries, lovebirds\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eShredding enrichment\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003e$6-10\u003c/td\u003e\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\u003ctd\u003ePenn-Plax Grass Mat\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003ePre-formed nest liner\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eEfficiency-focused breeders\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eQuick replacement, consistent\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003e$5-8\u003c/td\u003e\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\u003ctd\u003eA\u0026E Stainless Breeding Cage\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eDedicated breeding enclosure\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eSerious breeders\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eSterilizable, divider, exterior nest\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003e$100-200\u003c/td\u003e\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\u003ctd\u003eKaytee Exact Hand-Feeding\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eChick formula\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eHand-feeding breeders\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eComplete chick nutrition\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003e$10-15\u003c/td\u003e\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\u003ctd\u003eZoo Med Avian Calcium\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eCalcium+D3 supplement\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eAll breeding hens\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003ePrevents egg-binding and thin shells\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003e$6-10\u003c/td\u003e\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/table\u003e\n\n\u003ch2\u003eMaterials You MUST NEVER Put in a Bird\u0027s Nest\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCotton balls, cotton batting, or cotton string:\u003c/strong\u003e Cotton fibers wrap around chick toes and legs, constricting circulation and causing necrosis (dead tissue) — a chick can lose a toe or entire foot within 24 hours of a cotton fiber wrapping around it. This is not rare — it happens. Cotton also holds moisture and promotes bacterial growth. No cotton products, ever\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCedar or pine wood shavings:\u003c/strong\u003e Cedar contains aromatic oils (phenols) that are toxic to birds\u0027 respiratory systems — it causes respiratory distress, liver damage, and can be fatal. Pine shavings (unless kiln-dried specifically for pet use) contain similar aromatic compounds in lower concentrations. Aspen shavings are the only safe wood-shaving bedding for bird nests — aspen contains no aromatic oils\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHuman hair, pet fur (dog/cat), or yarn:\u003c/strong\u003e Hair and fur wrap around chick legs as tightly as cotton fibers do, and yarn frays into individual strands that do the same. Additionally, dog and cat fur may contain flea/tick treatment residue (topical preventatives are toxic to birds)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDryer lint:\u003c/strong\u003e It looks like soft, fluffy nesting material — but dryer lint contains synthetic microfibers from clothing (polyester, nylon, acrylic — which birds can ingest but can\u0027t digest), residual laundry detergent and fabric softener (toxic to birds when ingested), and human skin cells that harbor bacteria. Never use dryer lint\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eNewspaper with colored ink:\u003c/strong\u003e Black-and-white newsprint ink is soy-based and generally safe (though newspaper doesn\u0027t make good nesting material). Colored ink, glossy magazine paper, and thermal-printed receipts contain heavy metals (lead, cadmium) and BPA — do not let birds shred these into nesting material or bedding\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eString, twine, or thread of any kind:\u003c/strong\u003e Same constriction danger as cotton fibers — but worse, because synthetic strings (nylon, polyester) are stronger and won\u0027t break when a struggling chick wraps a leg\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eSafe nesting materials: coconut coir, bamboo fiber, aspen shavings (kiln-dried), seagrass, palm fiber, sisal fiber, unbleached paper strips, natural hay (timothy, not alfalfa — alfalfa hay is too dusty). When in doubt, stick with coconut coir and bamboo fiber — they\u0027re universally safe.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch2\u003eFAQ\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMy single female cockatiel keeps laying eggs in her food bowl. How do I stop this?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThis is chronic egg-laying triggered by environmental cues: 12+ hours of daylight, high-fat/seed-heavy diet, and the presence of an enclosed space (the food bowl, especially a covered or deep one). Remove the triggering bowl (switch to shallow dishes that don\u0027t simulate a nest cavity), reduce daylight to 10 hours (cover the cage at 7 PM, uncover at 7 AM), reduce high-fat foods and seeds, remove any shredding materials, and avoid petting her back/wings (breeding stimulus). If she\u0027s already laid eggs, let her sit on them for 21 days (the natural incubation period) — removing the eggs prematurely triggers her to lay a replacement clutch, depleting her calcium further. After 21 days, remove the eggs and immediately implement the environmental changes to prevent the next clutch. Chronic layers may need a hormone-suppressing implant (administered by an avian vet) if environmental changes alone don\u0027t stop the cycle.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDo I need to provide a nest box to a non-breeding single bird?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eGenerally, no. Providing a nest box to a single bird (especially a female) triggers hormonal behavior — egg-laying (even unfertilized eggs), territorial aggression around the box, and potentially chronic egg-laying that leads to calcium depletion, egg-binding, and reproductive disease. For enrichment during breeding season, provide shredding toys (coconut fiber mats, palm leaf shredders, paper rolls) that let the bird chew and shred — satisfying the nest-building instinct without providing a nest cavity that triggers egg production. If you do provide a nest box, be prepared for eggs — and the health risks that accompany egg production in single hens.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHow do I know if my breeding hen needs calcium supplementation?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eALL breeding hens need calcium supplementation — this is not optional. The calcium demand of forming eggshells exceeds what a normal diet (even a well-balanced pellet+vegetable diet) provides. Signs of calcium deficiency: thin-shelled or soft-shelled eggs (the egg collapses when removed from the nest), eggs with rough or irregular shell texture, the hen straining to pass an egg (possible egg-binding — this is a veterinary emergency), or the hen laying fewer eggs than expected for her species (the body conserves calcium by reducing clutch size when calcium is low). Provide powdered calcium with D3 on soft food daily during breeding season, plus a free-choice source (cuttlebone or mineral block) at all times.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch2\u003eConclusion\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFor the essential nest box infrastructure, \u003cstrong\u003ePrevue Pet Products Wooden Breeding Boxes\u003c/strong\u003e at $12-25 provide the humidity-regulating pine wood cavity that small and medium parrots instinctively seek — the concave floor keeps the clutch together under the brooding hen and the hinged lid enables essential nest inspection. Line the box with \u003cstrong\u003eKordon Nature\u0027s Nest Coconut Fiber\u003c/strong\u003e at $8-12 per brick — the most natural, antimicrobial nest lining that regulates humidity perfectly and prevents the splayed-leg deformity that slick nest surfaces cause.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFor the behavioral enrichment of nest-building, \u003cstrong\u003eLiving World Bamboo Nesting Fiber\u003c/strong\u003e at $6-10 provides the shredding and weaving activity that finches, canaries, and lovebirds actively engage in — loose fiber triggers the complete nest-building behavioral sequence. For breeders who prioritize cleanliness and efficiency, \u003cstrong\u003ePenn-Plax Grass Nest Liners\u003c/strong\u003e at $5-8 lift out and replace in seconds between clutches.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFor dedicated breeding operations, \u003cstrong\u003eA\u0026E Stainless Steel Breeding Cages\u003c/strong\u003e at $100-200 provide rust-proof, fully-sterilizable enclosures with divider panels and exterior nest box mounts — the professional-grade equipment that serious breeders invest in. For hand-feeding breeders, \u003cstrong\u003eKaytee Exact Hand-Feeding Formula\u003c/strong\u003e at $10-15 is the decades-established complete chick nutrition — but hand-feeding requires hands-on training from an experienced breeder or avian vet (hand-feeding mistakes are invariably fatal).\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eAnd the single supplement no breeding hen should be without: \u003cstrong\u003eZoo Med Avian Calcium with D3\u003c/strong\u003e at $6-10 — sprinkled on soft food daily during egg-laying cycles, this prevents calcium-depleted thin shells, egg-binding emergencies, and the long-term metabolic bone disease that silently develops in breeding hens. Cut cuttlebone and mineral blocks are good; powdered calcium with D3 on food is essential.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eRemember: a properly prepared nest box and nesting material supports a successful clutch — but the wrong material (cotton fibers, cedar shavings, dryer lint, pet hair) can kill chicks within hours. Stick with coconut coir, bamboo fiber, and aspen shavings — the materials that nature designed for nesting — and your breeding season will be healthier for it.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003eAffiliate Disclosure: PawCritic.com participates in the Amazon Services LLC Associates Program. We may earn commissions from qualifying purchases at no extra cost to you.\u003c/em\u003e\u003c/p\u003e"
