8+ hours at a time inside it, it\u0027s too small for your ferret.\n\n### Bar Spacing\n\nThis is non-negotiable. Ferrets can squeeze through gaps as small as 1 inch thanks to their famously flexible skeletons. Look for cages with **bar spacing of 1 inch or less** (ideally 1/2\" to 5/8\" if you have kits). Anything wider is an escape hatch — and ferrets *will* find it.\n\n### Material and Durability\n\nFerret cages take a beating. Your ferret will climb, dig, chew, and occasionally throw things against the bars. Opt for:\n\n- **Powder-coated steel** frames — durable, rust-resistant, and ferret-safe\n- **Solid plastic or metal trays** for the base (no wooden bases — ferrets will destroy them and wood absorbs odors)\n- **Secure latches** — spring-loaded or double-latch systems that clever ferrets can\u0027t pop open\n\n### Multi-Level Design\n\nFerrets are natural climbers and love vertical space. Cages with multiple levels, ramps, and platforms give your ferret more usable territory and keep them entertained. Look for solid ramps (not wire — wire ramps can hurt their feet) with good traction.\n\n### Ease of Cleaning\n\nFerrets are not the cleanest roommates. Their bedding needs regular washing, their litter boxes need daily scooping, and their entire cage needs a deep clean at least once a week. Choose a cage with:\n\n- Removable trays at the bottom\n- Doors that open wide for full access\n- Removable platforms/shelves for thorough cleaning\n\n### Litter Box Compatibility\n\nMost ferret owners train their ferrets to use a litter box in the cage. Make sure the cage has enough floor space to accommodate a corner litter pan without crowding the rest of the living area.\n\n### Portability and Assembly\n\nIf you plan to move the cage around, clean behind it regularly, or store it when not in use, consider weight, wheel options, and how complicated the assembly is. Some cages require tools; others snap together.\n\n---\n\n## Top Picks: Best Ferret Cages of 2026\n\nHere are 