ending on their natural habitat, but consistency is key. Use a timer to maintain a regular light/dark cycle year-round. Never leave UVB lights on 24/7 鈥?reptiles need darkness for proper melatonin production and sleep cycles.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n\u003cdiv class=\"faq-item\"\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"faq-question\"\u003eQ: Can I use a regular halogen or LED bulb for UVB?\u003c/div\u003e\n    \u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eA:\u003c/strong\u003e No. Standard halogen, incandescent, and most consumer LED bulbs do not emit meaningful UVB radiation. Only bulbs specifically marketed as \"UVB\" contain the appropriate phosphor coatings and glass filters to emit UV wavelengths. Using a \"grow light\" LED does not provide the right spectrum either. You need a dedicated reptile UVB source.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n\u003cdiv class=\"faq-item\"\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"faq-question\"\u003eQ: How often should I replace my UVB bulb?\u003c/div\u003e\n    \u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eA:\u003c/strong\u003e Linear T5/T8 fluorescent tubes should be replaced every 12 months at minimum, even if they still produce visible light. Mercury vapor bulbs (MVBs) should be replaced every 12鈥?8 months. The UVB output degrades well before the visible light output drops, so \"it\u0027s still bright\" is not a reliable indicator. Mark the installation date on your calendar.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n\u003cdiv class=\"faq-item\"\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"faq-question\"\u003eQ: Should I use a UV index meter to measure my light?\u003c/div\u003e\n    \u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eA:\u003c/strong\u003e If you\u0027re serious about precision lighting, a UV index meter (such as the Solarmeter 6.5) is an excellent investment. It measures the actual UVB intensity in UV Index units. A reading of 1.0鈥?.0 at the basking spot is appropriate for most forest species; 2.0鈥?.0 for arid species; and 4.0鈥?.0 for desert baskers. Without a meter, you\u0027re guessing based on brand claims and distance.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n\u003cdiv class=\"faq-item\"\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"faq-question\"\u003eQ: Do geckos and nocturnal species need UVB?\u003c/div\u003e\n    \u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eA:\u003c/strong\u003e Research from the past decade strongly suggests that even traditionally \"nocturnal\" species like crested geckos and leopard geckos benefit from low-level UVB exposure. They may not need the high outputs required by desert baskers, but a 5鈥?% T5 tube can improve overall health, immune function, and activity levels. The Arcadia 6% Forest kit is an excellent choice for these species.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n\u003cdiv class=\"faq-item\"\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"faq-question\"\u003eQ: Can I use a UVB light and a heat lamp on the same dome?\u003c/div\u003e\n    \u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eA:\u003c/strong\u003e It depends on the type. You should never combine a mercury vapor bulb with a heat lamp in the same fixture 鈥?MVBs operate at very high surface temperatures and create a fire risk if paired with additional heat sources. For T5 or T8 linear tubes, the fixture should be mounted inside the enclosure (on the ceiling or screen) rather than in a dome. Separate ceramic heat emitters or radiant heat panels are safer for supplementing temperature alongside UVB.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n\u003cdiv class=\"faq-item\"\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"faq-question\"\u003eQ: My reptile is showing MBD symptoms 鈥?will adding UVB fix it?\u003c/div\u003e\n    \u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eA:\u003c/strong\u003e Adding UVB is essential, but severe MBD requires immediate veterinary attention. A reptile veterinarian can diagnose MBD through blood tests and physical examination. They may administer injectable calcium and vitamin D3, and in advanced cases, may need to address secondary infections or deformities. UVB is preventive medicine 鈥?it\u0027s not a cure once the disease has set in. Early intervention is critical.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n\u003cdiv class=\"faq-item\"\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"faq-question\"\u003eQ: Do I need a separate UVA light?\u003c/div\u003e\n    \u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eA:\u003c/strong\u003e Most quality UVB bulbs also emit UVA as a byproduct, which is beneficial for vision and behavior but not critical for vitamin D3 synthesis. UVA helps reptiles see their environment more naturally and can stimulate feeding behavior. If you\u0027re using a reputable reptile UVB bulb (Arcadia, Zoo Med, Exo Terra), you\u0027re almost certainly getting adequate UVA. Separate UVA-only bulbs are generally unnecessary.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n\u003cdiv class=\"faq-item\"\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"faq-question\"\u003eQ: What\u0027s the difference between T5 and T8 tubes?\u003c/div\u003e\n    \u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eA:\u003c/strong\u003e T5 tubes (5/8\" diameter) are more energy-efficient, produce more light per watt, and have a higher output level than T8 tubes (8/8\" or 1\" diameter). T5 High Output (HO) tubes are the current gold standard for reptile UVB because they maintain effective UVB penetration in taller enclosures (\u003e18\"). T8 tubes are cheaper but less efficient and are gradually being phased out in favor of T5 in the reptile hobby.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n\u003cdiv class=\"faq-item\"\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"faq-question\"\u003eQ: Do screen lids block UVB?\u003c/div\u003e\n    \u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eA:\u003c/strong\u003e Yes 鈥?standard mesh and screen lids can reduce UVB transmission by 30鈥?0% depending on the mesh size and material. Tight-weave screen (like aluminum window screening) blocks more than loose-weave reptile mesh. If your fixture is mounted above a screen lid, account for this by either placing the light closer to the basking area or using a higher-output UVB source. Some keepers remove or modify screen lids on the basking side for better transmission.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n---\n\n\u003ch2\u003eConclusion\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eChoosing the right UVB light comes down to understanding your specific reptile\u0027s needs, your enclosure setup, and your budget. For most desert species (bearded dragons, frilled dragons, uromastyx), a \u003cstrong\u003eArcadia Desert 12% T5 HO\u003c/strong\u003e or \u003cstrong\u003eZoo Med ReptiSun 10.0 T5 HO\u003c/strong\u003e tube paired with a quality fixture remains the gold standard in 2026 鈥?reliable, consistent, and proven by thousands of reptile keepers worldwide.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFor forest species (crested geckos, gargoyle geckos, anoles, box turtles), the \u003cstrong\u003eArcadia Pro T5 D3 Forest Kit\u003c/strong\u003e offers the most precisely calibrated output. If you need an all-in-one heat + light solution for a large enclosure or outdoor setup, the \u003cstrong\u003eExo Terra Solar Glo 125W\u003c/strong\u003e or \u003cstrong\u003eMega-Ray Mega 160\u003c/strong\u003e are the most trusted mercury vapor options on the market.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eNo matter which light you choose, remember the golden rule: \u003cstrong\u003ereplace UVB bulbs every 12 months\u003c/strong\u003e, use a timer for consistent photoperiods, and monitor your reptile for early signs of deficiency. Consistent, quality UVB lighting is the single most impactful change you can make in your reptile\u0027s daily care routine 鈥?and the investment pays dividends in health, longevity, and quality of life.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp class=\"affiliate-disclosure\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAffiliate Disclosure:\u003c/strong\u003e PawCritic is a participant in the Amazon Services LLC Associates Program, an affiliate advertising program designed to provide a means for sites to earn advertising fees by advertising and linking to Amazon.com. We may earn a commission from qualifying purchases made through links in this article at no additional cost to you. This does not affect our editorial indepe