rgrown beak, consult an avian vet鈥攜ou don\u0027t want to risk cutting into the sensitive beak tissue. A volcanic mineral stone or natural grooming perch can help maintain beak shape between vet visits.\n\n**What if my bird bleeds during nail trimming?**\n\nKeep a pet-specific styptic powder or cornstarch on hand. If you cut the quick (the blood vessel inside the nail), apply pressure with the styptic powder and hold steady for 10鈥?5 seconds. Most bleeding stops quickly. If it doesn\u0027t, contact your vet.\n\n**Should I bathe my bird as part of grooming?**\n\nYes! Regular bathing or misting is essential for feather health. Use a spray bottle on a fine mist setting or a shallow dish for birds who enjoy bathing. Feather Fresh spray can add extra hydration, but nothing replaces plain water baths. Bathing helps condition feathers and reduces dust and dander.\n\n**Are sand perches safe for all birds?**\n\nMost birds benefit from sand perches, but some birds with arthritis or sensitive foot skin may find them uncomfortable. Rotate sand perches with softer natural wood perches to give feet a break. Always supervise new perch introductions.\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion\n\nBird grooming is a fundamental part of responsible companion parrot ownership. From daily beak maintenance using volcanic mineral stones to weekly nail trims with professional clippers, having the right supplies makes the routine easier, safer, and less stressful for both you and your bird.\n\nOur top picks for 2026 span the full grooming spectrum: the Rolf C. Hagen Coral Calcium for internal beak health, the Lincoln Precision Pro Clippers for versatile trimming, the KAKEI Professional Nail Clipper for scissor-style precision, and the Featherland Paradise Sand Perch for passive, everyday grooming. Don\u0027t overlook the Feather Fresh spray for feather shine and hydration, and consider adding a flight harness for supervised outdoor exercise.\n\nBuild your grooming kit gradually, introduce tools slowly so your 